ce:section.ce:para:
The three kinds of different receptors-functionalized CDs (BA-CDs, Van-CDs and PM-CDs) were facilely synthesized through a one-pot method according to a previously reported work with slight modifications [21]. Transmission electron microscopy (TEM) images were used to estimate the morphologies of the synthesized CDs. Three kinds of CDs showed the similar size of 3–6 nm with spherical structure and good uniformity (Fig. 1
                        ). The chemical bonds and functional groups of the as-prepared CDs were confirmed by X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) spectra (Fig. 2
                        ). The peaks of PM-CDs and Van-CDs correspond to the elements of C 1 s, N 1 s, and O 1 s, respectively. While peaks of BA-CDs can be attributed to C 1 s, N 1 s, O 1 s and B 1 s [29]. The results indicate the successful synthesis of the corresponding CDs. The zeta potentials of the CDs were studied at neutral pH to study the surface charge density. The results indicate that all the three kinds of CDs have high negative zeta potential which may be attributed to the carboxyl groups present on the CDs (Fig. 3
                        ).

To study the performances of the fluorescence sensing array to discriminate multiple analytes, we selected six kinds of bacteria with different size and morphologies, including E. coli, P. aeruginosa, D. desulfuricans, S. sciuri, L. monocytogenes and S. aureus. Fig. 7

                        A shows the fluorescence response pattern of the three kinds of CDs after incubation with six kinds of bacteria. The relative fluorescence intensity variety for six kinds of bacteria towards the CDs are significantly different, which could be attributed to the binding ability differences of bacteria towards CDs since the size, morphologies and surface chemical component of bacteria are quite different. The resultant fluorescence response pattern was then analysed using LDA, a widely used mathematical statistical method in sensing array system to maximize the separation ability of the sensor array [30]. Ten replicates were tested for each kind of bacteria in each CDs, producing a training matrix (three CDs× 6 bacteria× 10 replicates) (Table S1). Then, the matrix was handled by the analysis software SPSS (version 22.0). Three canonical factors (86.5%, 12.7%, and 0.8%) were generated for the total variance. And a 2D plot was generated using the first two most significant discrimination factors (Fig. 7B), where each point represents the fluorescence response of three CDs to one kind of bacteria. Six kinds of bacteria were clearly separated into six clusters without overlap, and the discrimination accuracy was 100% for each kind of bacteria according to Jackknife classification (Table 1
                        ), indicating the effective discrimination ability of the CDs-based sensor array against bacteria. Meanwhile, the sensor array could not separate the 6 kinds of bacteria from each other (Fig. S1), when using any two kinds recognition molecules. Hence, the results also suggest that more kinds of bacteria could be identified by using more kinds of different recognition molecules functionalized CDs.
